My family has traditionally prepared a celeriac salad, from grated celeriac and apples, with vegetable oil (usually rapeseed), a bit of sugar and salt and a hint of freshly minced garlic. It also works with carrot in lieu of celeriac, and you can skip the garlic if it seems weird. Also, my mother sometimes mashed some cooked celeriac and potatoes with butter for a delicious, creamy dinner side dish. My maternal grandmother often served diced, boiled and buttered kohlrabi as a side dish - but she was notoriously bad at removing the fibrous bits of the vegetable. I still remember having to spit them out as a kid during dinner at grandma's. She also added lemon juice to way too many things, but not kohlrabi, thankfully.

I just realized English uses the word "salad" where us Polish people would use either "sałatka" or "surówka". "Sałatka" is generally used to describe any cold dish consisting mostly of vegetables. "Surówka" ("surowy" means raw, so "surówka" is literally "the raw stuff") is generally never a stand-alone dish but rather a side dish, and always made of raw fruit or veg. A "surówka" would never be called a "sałatka". So, Casar's salad is "sałatka Cezar" and a Nicoise salad "sałatka nicejska", while coleslaw (polonized as "kolesław") is most definitely a "surówka". The celeriac salad above is a Polish "surówka", too. To make this even more complicated, a leafy side dish is a "sałatka", not a "surówka". Why wont you be normal, Polish, oh why?!

